    "review": [
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "Michael McD"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I followed the recipe precisely, but after two days in the fridge, the mustard is very, very liquid. Any ideas on how to remedy this and why it happened?"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "ColbyP"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I made my first batch (a few months ago) of mustard using this recipe minus the brown sugar and it was quite spicy. To solve the spiciness, instead of cutting the mustard in the storage container with something, we would add a little bit of ketchup to our portion on our plate while having some and made it quite delightful.\n\nI went this route of making my own mustard is because our favorite mustard, Beaver's Deli Mustard is not gluten free and we're now a gluten free household."
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "twinsue"
            },
            "reviewBody": "The mustard should last a very long time. There isn't anything in it to spoil really withthe vinegar. I don't even keep my mustards in the fridge. I keep them in the cabinet and they have never gone bad!"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "pgaud0"
            },
            "reviewBody": "I realize the texture would be different, but how much yellow mustard powder would I use as a substitute?"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "Joshua Bousel"
            },
            "reviewBody": "@awinnerisyou I just made this last week, so I'm waiting it out to see just how long it'll last, but with so much vinegar, it should be good for a while. The issue I'd be concerned about is not so much it going bad, but how long until it loses its flavor, which mustards do as they age."
        }
